excerpt: 1400s frescoes & Renaissance art fill this former hospital, now a museum & exhibition complex.
detail_description: Santa Maria della Scala is a former hospital turned museum and exhibition complex in Siena. The structure, built as a hospital in the 11th century, has been transformed into an extraordinary complex featuring frescoes from the 1400s and Renaissance art. It includes restored pilgrims halls and the chapel of the Madonna, along with new additions such as an archaeological museum, children's museum, modern bar, and bookshop.
name: Santa Maria della Scala
address: Piazza del Duomo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 87m-high square stone tower, built from 1325 to 1348, with a belfry dedicated to the Virgin Mary.
detail_description: The Torre del Mangia is an 87-meter-high square stone tower in Siena, Italy, built from 1325 to 1348. It features a belfry dedicated to the Virgin Mary and is a prominent landmark in the city's skyline. The tower is part of the Siena Cathedral complex, which has a rich history dating back to the 9th century. The cathedral underwent significant expansion and renovation over the centuries, resulting in its impressive architectural design.
name: Torre del Mangia
address: Il Campo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza del Campo is a must-visit destination in Siena, Italy. This historic square has been the city's focal point since the 14th century and offers a unique nine-segment shell shape. Surrounded by notable landmarks such as Palazzo Civico, Torre del Mangia, and Fonte Gaia, visitors can immerse themselves in the daily life of the city.
name: Piazza del Campo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Severe Gothic cathedral with a frescoed chapel housing relics of St Catherine, including her head.
detail_description: Basilica Cateriniana San Domenico is a striking Gothic cathedral in Siena, Italy. Built in the 13th century, it is renowned for its association with St. Catherine of Siena, who was declared a patron saint of Italy. The basilica houses a frescoed chapel displaying relics of St. Catherine, including her head and finger on a marble altar from 1469.
name: Basilica Cateriniana San Domenico
address: Piazza S. Domenico, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Siena, a city in central Italy’s Tuscany region, is distinguished by its medieval brick buildings. The fan-shaped central square, Piazza del Campo, is the site of the Palazzo Pubblico, the Gothic town hall, and Torre del Mangia, a slender 14th-century tower with sweeping views from its distinctive white crown. The city’s 17 historic “contrade” (districts) extend outward from the piazza.
detail_description: Siena, located in Tuscany, Italy, is known for its medieval brick buildings and historic landmarks. The city's central square, Piazza del Campo, features the Palazzo Pubblico and the Torre del Mangia. Siena Cathedral is a prominent place of worship with a rich history dating back to the 9th century.
name: Siena
address: 53100 Province of Siena, Italy

excerpt: 13th century brick town hall with tower housing the civic museum & its fresco collection.
detail_description: Palazzo Pubblico is a 13th-century brick town hall located in Piazza del Campo, Siena. It was built to house the Government of Nine of the Republic of Siena and now serves as the City Hall.
name: Palazzo Pubblico
address: Il Campo, 1, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Gallery housing vast collection of Sienese masterpieces from the late medieval to Renaissance era.
detail_description: The Pinacoteca Nazionale di Siena is a must-visit for art enthusiasts, showcasing a vast collection of Sienese masterpieces from the late medieval to Renaissance era. Housed in the medieval Palazzo Bonsignori, this national museum features works by renowned artists such as Domenico Beccafumi, Duccio di Buoninsegna, and Michelino Molinari da Besozzo.
name: Pinacoteca Nazionale di Siena
address: Via S. Pietro, 29, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Monumental fountain in a plaza with Old Testament reliefs & statues such as a Madonna & Child.
detail_description: Bar Ristorante Fonte Gaia is nestled in the heart of Siena, right by the iconic Piazza del Campo. This vibrant spot not only offers a delightful dining experience but also immerses visitors in the rich history surrounding it. The nearby monumental fountain, known as Fonte Gaia, is a beloved symbol for locals and features stunning reliefs and statues that tell biblical stories.
name: Bar Ristorante Fonte Gaia
address: Il Campo, 21/23, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: 13th-century structure famed for its facade & its marble stripes in symbolic black & white.
detail_description: Siena Cathedral, also known as the Duomo, is a 13th-century marvel renowned for its striking facade with symbolic black and white marble stripes. It stands as the main place of worship in Siena and dominates the city's skyline alongside the Torre del Mangia. The cathedral has a rich history, originally built to replace a church dedicated to Mary on a site that was once a temple for the worship of Minerva.
name: Siena Cathedral
address: Piazza del Duomo, 8, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: St Catherine's home, now a sanctuary, with art-filled oratory, church & Catherine's frescoed cell.
detail_description: Santuario Casa di Santa Caterina is a religious complex dedicated to honoring the life of Saint Catherine of Siena, one of Italy's patron saints. The sanctuary encompasses various structures such as an art-filled oratory, church, and Catherine's frescoed cell. It is believed to be built over her original birthplace and offers visitors the opportunity to explore her birth home where she was born in 1347 as the 23rd of 25 children.
name: Santuario Casa di Santa Caterina
address: Costa Sant'Antonio, 6, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Observation point atop an unfinished church facade, with views of centuries-old towers & piazzas.
detail_description: Facciatone, located atop an unfinished church facade near the Duomo di Siena, offers a breathtaking panoramic view of Siena and the picturesque Tuscan countryside. Accessible with an admission ticket to the Duomos OPA Museo, this observation point requires climbing several stairs but rewards visitors with stunning vistas of historical landmarks such as the Duomo di Siena, Torre del Mangia, Piazza del Campo, and ancient city walls.
name: Facciatone
address: Piazza del Duomo, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Majestic, airy library within the Siena Duomo known for its soaring, vibrant Pinturicchio frescoes.
detail_description: The Piccolomini Library is a stunning and airy library located within the Siena Duomo. It is renowned for its magnificent Pinturicchio frescoes that adorn the walls and vaulted ceiling. These vibrant frescoes depict scenes from the life of Pope Pius II and are considered to be of great art-historical significance.
name: Piccolomini Library
address: Piazza del Duomo, 8, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

name: PALIO DI SIENA PHOTOGRAPHY
address: Via Mentana, 24 A, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza del Mercato is a bustling square in Siena that offers a vibrant atmosphere and a glimpse into the city's history. Once used for public executions and as a Roman marketplace, it has transformed into a lively hub with diverse merchandise stalls and charming eateries.
name: Piazza del Mercato
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Embark on a delightful Chianti wine tour and immerse yourself in the picturesque vineyards and wineries of the renowned Montalcino region. Indulge in the rich history and winemaking traditions as you visit multiple esteemed wineries, sampling a variety of exquisite wines along the way. Learn about the meticulous process of wine production while taking in panoramic views of the stunning Tuscan countryside.
name: Chianti wine tours Wine tour Montalcino
address: Via Paolo Frajese, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Bar Il Palio is a must-visit spot in Siena, known for its annual horse race, the Palio. The city's Medieval historic center offers picturesque and untouched nature, making it an undeniably scenic destination. Visitors can wander through charming streets, visit museums and architectural gems, and attend events and festivals. During the Palio event at Il Campo, 17 neighborhoods compete in a thrilling horse race around the square, creating an electric atmosphere with spectators from all over the world.
name: Bar Il Palio
address: Il Campo, 47, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Palazzo Piccolomini is a stunning example of Renaissance architecture located in the vibrant heart of Siena. Perched on Banchi di Sotto and adjacent to Rinaldini Street, this historic palace offers breathtaking views and is conveniently close to significant sites like the church of San Martino and Palazzo delle Papesse, which also has ties to the influential Piccolomini family.
name: Palazzo Piccolomini
address: Banchi di Sotto, 52, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Piazza del Duomo in Siena is a bustling square filled with historical and cultural attractions. The area is home to the stunning Cathedral of Santa Maria Assunta, featuring an impressive Romanesque-Gothic facade and a remarkable interior with intricate religious symbolism on its floors.
name: Piazza del Duomo
address: 53100 Siena SI, Italy

detail_description: Palazzo Chigi-Saracini, also known as Palazzo Piccolomini or Palazzo delle Papesse, is a prestigious noble palace located in Siena, Italy. Built between 1460 and 1495 by Caterina Piccolomini, sister of Pope Pius II, the palazzo features a facade reminiscent of Florentine buildings from the same period.
name: Palazzo Chigi-Saracini
address: Via di Città, 89, 53100 Siena SI, Italy

excerpt: Church featuring a gothic brick facade & an uncluttered, marble-banded interior with a wood ceiling.
detail_description: Located near Piazza del Campo, the Basilica of San Francesco is a significant church in Siena. Built in the 13th century in Romanesque style and later expanded into a magnificent Gothic structure, it features a gothic brick facade and a marble-banded interior with a wooden ceiling. The basilica holds historical significance as the site of the Eucharistic miracle of the stolen hosts, which were later found and returned after three centuries.
name: Basilica of San Francesco
address: Piazza S. Francesco, 5, 53100 Siena SI, Italy
